 *1225658010* Affiliates
 If I use Amazon EC2 for a server to run Saichuji2 (with battle function & AI written in C++ or Haskell), it will cost me about $73 per month on an ongoing basis. I was wondering what to do about it, but then I was told, "Why don't you just put up ads and collect the money? That's right, if I create a service that earns more than $73/month, I don't have to think about the server cost.
 
 So I tried to create a Google AdSense account, but...it comes by check? That's a hassle. So I changed my target to a Japanese company. Also, I'm going to put it here because this blog has more page views than the game in the middle of the day.
 
 
 <a href='http://www.valuecommerce.ne.jp/'>Value Commerce</a>, It was my fault too for mistaking my e-mail address when I registered, but I'm having trouble registering with the same URL even though there should have been an error. It seems that the URL is not normalized, so I removed the trailing slash and it went through. But for some reason, it also asks me to enter the title of the site, so I'm getting conflicts there too. I wonder if it's a specification that sites with the same title can't be registered. I wonder how it works.
 
 
 <a href="http://www.j-a-net.jp/" target="_blank">JANet</a><img src="http://text.j-a-net.jp/1050611/1040/" width="1" height="1" border="0 The "JANet" is a service that handles money, but it has a ridiculous specification that the password must be alphanumeric and up to 10 characters. Well, the explanation may have been the most helpful. I was surprised that the input form has voice guidance, though.
 
 
 <a href="http://click.j-a-net.jp/1050611/240440/" target="_blank">Smart-C<img src="http://text.j-a-net.jp/1050611/240440/" height="1" width="1" border="0"></a>. Is this for a mobile site? I know this blog can be viewed from a cell phone, but I wonder if it's worth putting it here.
 
 
 And this kind of thing is supposed to be checked by a human to see if it's okay as an ad serving medium. I've gone so far as to create an account in a late-night fling, but for now, I guess I'll just have to wait, since no one inside is working at this late hour of the night. I have a feeling I'll be bored by the time it gets approved.
 
 
 Since I'm here, I'll post the link, though it's flying. <a href="http://click.j-a-net.jp/1050611/11675/" target="_blank">Finally, zero yen commission! FX Prime<img src="http://text.j-a-net.jp/1050611/11675/" height="1" width="1" border="0"></a>, <a href="http://click.j-a-net.jp/ 1050611/11676/" target="_blank">FX from 10,000 yen. FX Prime "Selectable Gaika" <img src="http://text.j-a-net.jp/1050611/11676/" height="1" width="1" border="0 "></a>. I don't know if this is the first time in Japan to offer zero yen commission. At any rate, they are offering 2000 yen cash back campaign until the end of December.
 
 *1225664339* noticed
 I was surprised to see so many affiliates offering a few yen per click, but when I think about it calmly, even if I posted one such link every day and 30 people clicked on it every day, it would still be 900 yen per month. Some of them pay 3 yen or so, but that's a minority. I'm starting to feel barren already.
 
 Oh, but I think it might be helpful in the future to see the number of times each link is displayed and clicked on, so I'll keep doing that for a while.
 
 *1225703557*Affiliate of the person OK type
 I want to experience it myself and then blog about it, but the dilemma is that I have to experience it after stepping on the link I wrote about it. w
 I'll just post the link for now and edit it later.
 
